That's an interesting question. In the C language SGP4 code that this Python implementation is based on, the result is returned as:
https://celestrak.com/publications/AIAA/2006-6753/AIAA-2006-6753-Rev2.pdf
```
 if (mrt < 1.0)
 {
// printf("# decay condition %11.6f \n",mrt);
 satrec.error = 6;
 return false;
 } 
```
The problem with returning anything other than `false` is that normal users would think that the satellite were still flying, and would expect it to be at exactly the returned coordinates, because in those cases where the algorithm does not return `false`, users think that they can use the position as a real position for the satellite.

Can you adjust your algorithm so that it searches for the moment when the satellite transitions from a valid SGP4 position to the moment where this routine returns `false`, and compute your re-entry from there? If you wait until a moment when this returns `false`, then I think you are already past the point where SGP4 can return good positions, and you will be running Newton's method on an invalid starting point.

