You already can set your own options class (just inherit from ~~`ModelOptions`~~ `SchemaOptions`):

```python
class FooOptions(SchemaOptions):
    def __init__(self, test=None, **kwargs):
        super(FooOptions, self).__init__(**kwargs)
        self.test = test

class Foo(Model):
    __optionsclass__ = FooOptions
    class Options:
        test = 123
```

@timdp you have it exactly right. Peru ignores the fact that your override path is a git repo, and it just copies the files that it sees there. `reup` is unaffected by `override`, and it will still talk to your regular git URL to find the latest master. So like you said, you either need to push your new commits upstream before you `reup`, or you need to edit `peru.yaml` by hand. (Though if you push the new `peru.yaml` before you push the commits it refers to, other people who don't have your override will hit an error when they sync. This is one of the reasons that `reup` ignores `override`.)

Does this feel like the right way to do things? I'd love to get feedback if this design is inconvenient or confusing.

Another approach that's useful sometimes, is to edit your `peru.yaml` to replace the `url` field in your module with `/path/to/local/repo2`. That will make peru treat your local repo like a real git repo, so it'll fetch `rev` instead of just whatever's checked out, and `reup` will actually read your local `master`. If you do that, you'll need to be careful not to check in your only-locally-meaningful repo path, in addition to unpublished commits like above. I've only ever really needed this for testing, but if it was something that a lot of people wanted, we could consider supporting something like `overrides.yaml`, where you could put local edits to module fields without actually touching `peru.yaml` (and then you could add `overrides.yaml` to `.gitignore`.) It's not clear to me that that's a good idea -- it would be very confusing if you created that file and then forgot about it, for example --but I'm curious what other people think.

