@johnhuffsmith I've seen a few blog posts/SO answers with solutions like that, and it seems like a functional solution.

That said, I don't feel like a setup like that really makes sense--EB isn't telling you not to do stuff like that, but it isn't really supported by any of the EB systems.  Basically, you're running an EB instance like a non-EB EC2 instance, but with less control over the overall environment.  You get your source deployed, and your initialization scripts called, but there's nothing built into the EB control panel or APIs to support that kind of functionality (other than SSHing in and looking yourself, of course).

If you could run django-rq as a WSGI app, then you'd be able to set up a separate EB environment, like you would for a standard EB worker tier environment, and be able to take full advantage of EB's built-in monitoring, etc.  Plus, you could scale your workers based on workload, not along with web load.

@searchivarius Thanks again for the help. I really hope the build time would stay near-linear so that our time/speed assumptions would work for larger scale data.

I will let you know of the build times at a later date (as soon as I have the resources to test the library for large scale datasets).

Thanks again!
